{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"0b81a9e1dc7685e18d6e0cd7a819fbcd41ca66558d7f0d3f479057252f416530","slug":"pages.m17-case-q-q-2-of-3","location":"/pages/261-m17-case-q-q-2-of-3.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Case Q→Q (2 of 3)","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"Shawn Wiggins","given":"Shawn","family":"Wiggins"},"name":"Shawn Wiggins","affiliations":["City College of San Francisco"],"id":"contributors-myst-generated-uid-0"}],"license":{"content":{"id":"CC-BY-4.0","url":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","name":"Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International","free":true,"CC":true}},"affiliations":[{"id":"City College of San Francisco","name":"City College of San Francisco"}],"numbering":{"title":{"offset":2}},"exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"261-m17-case-q-q-2-of-3.md","url":"/build/261-m17-case-q-q-2-o-2ac81e5847de8ebdef7da2eff620ad34.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Learning Objectives","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"N715D7gncW"}],"key":"Ys3MKEMXRv"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"- In a given context, carry out the appropriate inferential method for examining relationships and draw the appropriate conclusions.\n- Specify the null and alternative hypotheses for comparing relationships.","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"Es0kQVHokv"}],"key":"EY0Vxnz333"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":1},"end":{"line":8,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Let’s introduce our leading example, which was actually our leading example in the Exploratory Data Analysis unit as well.","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":1},"end":{"line":8,"column":1}},"key":"a4emUFWxd4"}],"key":"LP6Ucn2JZF"},{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Example","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"rkqzM62cHs"}],"key":"cf5IdmyKBn"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"In a study of the legibility and visibility of highway signs, a Pennsylvania research firm determined the maximum distance at which each of 30 drivers could read a newly designed sign. The 30 participants in the study ranged in age from 18 to 82 years old. The government agency that funded the research hoped to improve highway safety for older drivers and wanted to examine the relationship between age and sign legibility distance. (Data adopted with permission from Utts and Heckard, Mind on Statistics).\n\nLet's go through the entire process (outlined on the previous page) for this example.\n\n*Starting point*: The researchers wanted to examine the relationship between age and sign legibility distance in the population of drivers. The researchers collected data from a random sample of 30 drivers:\n\n```{figure} images/image179.gif\n:alt: A two column table, with column headers &quot;Age&quot; and &quot;Distance.&quot; Here is the data in the table, by row (in &quot;Age: Distance&quot; format): 18: 510; 20: 590; 22: 560; 23: 510; 23: 460; 25: 490; 27: 560; ... ... 77: 360; 79: 310; 82: 360;\n\nA two column table, with column headers &quot;Age&quot; and &quot;Distance.&quot; Here is the data in the table, by row (in &quot;Age: Distance&quot; format): 18: 510; 20: 590; 22: 560; 23: 510; 23: 460; 25: 490; 27: 560; ... ... 77: 360; 79: 310; 82: 360;\n```\n\n*Exploratory Analysis:*\n\nThe researchers display the data on a scatterplot:\n\n```{figure} images/image147.gif\n:alt: A scatterplot of Distance vs. Age. Distance is on the vertical axis, and age is on the horizontal axis. The histogram has a negative relationship, and it seems like it could be reasonably linear.\n\nA scatterplot of Distance vs. Age. Distance is on the vertical axis, and age is on the horizontal axis. The histogram has a negative relationship, and it seems like it could be reasonably linear.\n```\n\nand observe a negative linear relationship in the data. In order to quantify the strength of that linear relationship, the researchers supplement the scatterplot with a numerical measure—the correlation coefficient (r), which turns out to be r = -.801, confirming the researchers' visual assessment of a negative, fairly strong linear relationship between age and legibility distance.","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"key":"cBHEgxCOgn"}],"key":"mdbTxYgi8e"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"QlewfVS1DO"}],"key":"C7vHdqWNkZ"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**Learn By Doing**\n\nCase Q→Q\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"key":"wAnPWBijnv"}],"key":"AHVyPgXvbL"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":44,"column":1},"end":{"line":44,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":44,"column":1},"end":{"line":44,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Inference:","position":{"start":{"line":44,"column":1},"end":{"line":44,"column":1}},"key":"w4kIQBph4k"}],"key":"wUgRgQufGe"}],"key":"g5fEhRjPlR"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":46,"column":1},"end":{"line":46,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The researchers would now like to see whether the observed linear relationship between age and legibility distance can be generalized to the entire population of drivers. In other words, the researchers want to check whether the observed linearity is due to true linearity in the population, or a pattern that could have happened just by chance.","position":{"start":{"line":46,"column":1},"end":{"line":46,"column":1}},"key":"cwwmbEzwgf"}],"key":"ZHYDt9xRxH"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The test that the researchers are going to carry out is a t-test (most commonly known as the “t-test for the slope” for reasons that we are not going to get into) which is testing the following two hypotheses (step 1):","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"key":"if7q8uAqRu"}],"key":"DJPrLoU17E"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":50,"column":1},"end":{"line":50,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":50,"column":1},"end":{"line":50,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"H","position":{"start":{"line":50,"column":1},"end":{"line":50,"column":1}},"key":"hYJGlomX8i"}],"key":"hGZtmNZ53Z"},{"type":"text","value":"*~o~**:* There is no linear relationship between age and distance.","position":{"start":{"line":50,"column":1},"end":{"line":50,"column":1}},"key":"bfq6y0957x"}],"key":"jV7yy2UWHf"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":52,"column":1},"end":{"line":52,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":52,"column":1},"end":{"line":52,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"H","position":{"start":{"line":52,"column":1},"end":{"line":52,"column":1}},"key":"SYegOVK4h6"}],"key":"g1cIzLpMsg"},{"type":"text","value":"*~a~**:* There is a linear relationship between age and distance.","position":{"start":{"line":52,"column":1},"end":{"line":52,"column":1}},"key":"l2aAdkh6cY"}],"key":"XRUSe3pvAg"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":54,"column":1},"end":{"line":54,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"and in general,","position":{"start":{"line":54,"column":1},"end":{"line":54,"column":1}},"key":"wF1izq8Xnk"}],"key":"pfXrupTvnd"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":56,"column":1},"end":{"line":56,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":56,"column":1},"end":{"line":56,"column":1}},"children":[{"typ